All these test fail.

I have just created a different but related PR (https://github.com/apache/incubator-groovy/pull/21). It turns @Canonical into a meta-annotation (aka alias/aggregate/collector). It doesn't provide exactly what you're after but comes very close, e.g.:

```
import groovy.transform.*
@Canonical
class Foo {
    int a
}
@Canonical(callSuper=true, includeSuperProperties=true, includeNames=true)
class Bar extends Foo {
    int b
}
@Canonical(callSuper=true, includeSuper=true)
@TupleConstructor(includeSuperProperties=true)
class Baz extends Foo {
    int b
}
def (b1, b2, b3) = [new Bar(a:5, b:20), new Bar(10, 20), new Baz(15, 20)]
assert [b1, b2, b3].toString() == '[Bar(b:20, a:5), Bar(b:20, a:10), Baz(20, Foo(15))]'
assert b1 != b2
assert b1.hashCode() != b2.hashCode()
```

More importantly, the plumbing done to enable the above PR would prohibit the proposals you have here but would allow you to define your own @SuperCanonical or whatever that had exactly the semantics that you would like without any AST-level programming by defining your own meta-annotation, e.g.:

```
import groovy.transform.*

@ToString(includeSuperProperties=true)
@TupleConstructor(includeSuperProperties=true)
@EqualsAndHashCode(callSuper=true)
@AnnotationCollector
@interface SuperCanonical { }

@Canonical
class Foo {
  int a
}
@SuperCanonical
class Bar extends Foo {
  int b
}
def (b1, b2) = [new Bar(a:5, b:20), new Bar(10, 20)]
assert [b1, b2].toString() == '[Bar(20, 5), Bar(20, 10)]'
assert b1 != b2
assert b1.hashCode() != b2.hashCode()
```

Let me know if you have any feedback.

I have the feeling that this code will still ignore methods coming from an interface that has been extended, especially if there are multiple such interfaces.  

```
interface SomeInterface {void foo()}
interface AnotherInterface extends SomeInterface;
abstract class Parent implements AnotherInterface;
abstract abstract class Child extends Parent{ void bar(){foo()}}
```
